by Wexas » Sun Jun 21, 2020 2:02 pm

Tamakuni wrote:Dwinpantara is actually the fourteenth province, located in Southeast Asia, of the Khilafah Islamiyah nation-state. As the new regime only had control of the province to 'spread islam', the province performed economically badly and often found itself relying on donations from the Khilafah Islamiyah central government located more than 7 thousand km away. In the 90s, oil prices collapsed, creating widespread unrest and giving birth to the Alliance to Restore the Republic, which aims to free Dwinpantara from the control of the central Khilafah Islamiyah government.

Their primary religion of Kabiism has several different branches, the Ikakami, Faylcan Kabiists, and Frianese Kabiists. While the Ikakami do not have much information on them, I believe they could be considered the Kabi Orthodox with the other two branches being ethnic-based splinter groups. The division between Faylcan Kabiists and Frianese Kabiists appears to be entirely doctrinal, with the color of their god being the main division. Which, on face value, sounds a tad silly as most doctrinal disputes throughout history have more to do with theological questions such as the nature of their God or entrance into the afterlife rather than the aesthetics of the God, but the factbook is still WIP so I will reserve judgement.

It is to be noted that, despite being a Democracy, the leader in charge is not a Kabiist or even a Shinto but is rather agnostic (which are no more than 2.9% of the population according to the factbooks). Statistically speaking, it is rare for such small minorities to become a leader in a democracy, so it could be a sign that Tamakuni is much more progressive than the rest of the world.

Ninja'd, Give me a sec

AN: Pianos are the primary export in the nation. However, the AN does not go into detail about why this is the case. This could mean that the ivory is a very common resource in the nation, the old material used in piano keys. However, given the Germanic origin of the nation, I find this to be unlikely. Perhaps it could be a consequence of a cultured upper-class with in the nation, as (especially grand) pianos are often associated with a highly cultured form of the upper class not found in today's society. Or, it could be the opposite, it could be a subtle hint of how the nation sells itself out to richer powers in order to get itself wealthy, being the manufacturing hub for nations of a much higher status than it. Oooor, it could just be something picked at random and I am just overthinking it. I am honestly quite interested to see if the AN will ever expand upon it (not that the AN has to, just that I would be interested if they do).
